            <h4>Learning to code</h4>
            <p>I first encountered programming near 2003 in the educational game <a href = "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Colobot">Colobot</a>, where an object-oriented programming language syntactically similar to C++ and Java is used to program robots during a space mission. The programming concepts I learned there turned out to be quite useful later on.</p>
            <p>The first step to become a web developer was an introduction-level HTML, CSS and JavaScript course on <a href = "https://www.coursera.org/learn/html-css-javascript-for-web-developers">Coursera</a>. The instructors style made it easy to follow and it was quite rewarding to see my code transform into visual elements, not just a result in the console. After a while I came up with my own ideas on what to create next and read the necessary documentations and tutorials until I was able to make it. It also helped me prove that I am able to learn by myself and to realise that knowledge is out there if you are willing to reach. Fortunately I also had a professional mentor to consult from time to time about my progress and the issues I have encountered.</p>
            <p>Node.js was chosen for backend due to its popularity and the for the very practical reason that I already knew the basics of JavaScript at that point. The methodology was the same - after learning the ropes from online courses I just created mini-projects for myself, divided them into elemental tasks and looked for their solution.</p>
            <p>At the moment I feel myself capable of building a personal or a small-business website with basic functionality and the ability for the user to create and edit its contents.</p>
